A regular hexagon with side length \(a = 3\) can be divided into 6 equilateral triangles, each with side length 3.

The area of one equilateral triangle is \(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \times a^2 = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \times 9 = \frac{9\sqrt{3}}{4}\).

Thus, the total area is \(6 \times \frac{9\sqrt{3}}{4} = \frac{54\sqrt{3}}{4} = \frac{27\sqrt{3}}{2}\).

\[
\boxed{
\begin{matrix}
\text{area} \\ = \\ \dfrac{ \\ 27 \\ \sqrt{ \\ \, \\ 3 \\ \, \\ } \\ \\ }{ \\ 2 \\ } \end{matrix}
}
\]
